Most users will have the javascript in their cache anyway, so they won't even be hitting the CDN. Also, why not check to see if the object exists before doing anything else?<p><pre><code>    <script id="jquery" src="http://code.google.com/jquery.js"></script>
    <script>
    if (jQuery == undefined) {
        document.querySelector("#jquery").src = 'Backup CDN';
    }
    </script>
</code></pre>
That should work, in theory, if not then just remove script#jquery, create a new one and append to the document before executing any script(s).

And if you want to avoid changing the rest of the page:<p><script>
  var oldAlertFunction = window.alert;
  window.alert = function(){};
  </script><p><pre><code>  <script src="crockford.com/json.library.js"></script>
</code></pre>
<script>
window.alert=oldAlertFunction;
</script>
